      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">2. Heat-cycle URL cannibalization fix</h3>
      <p>
        Three URLs were competing for the same dog-heat queries: <code>/dog-heat-cycle-calculator</code> (winning, position 32), <code>/heat-cycle-tracking</code> (orphan, position 50), and <code>/tools/heat-cycle-calculator</code> (position 42). Reframed <code>/heat-cycle-tracking</code> as the species-neutral software/workflow page ("Heat Cycle Tracking Software for Breeders") instead of competing on the same calculator queries. Added a top-of-page link from there to <code>/dog-heat-cycle-calculator</code> for users who actually want the calculator. <code>/dog-heat-cycle-calculator</code> remains the canonical answer for dog-anchored calculator queries; <code>/tools/heat-cycle-calculator</code> remains the canonical answer for the tool surface. Each URL now has a clear job.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">3. Tool-sibling cross-linking</h3>
      <p>
        The heat-cycle calculator pages are pulling 99% of free-tool traffic. The other seven free tools (breeding planner, progesterone timing tracker, whelping date calculator, puppy application builder, puppy vaccination/deworming/weight) are stuck at zero impressions because Google hasn't found them through enough inbound paths. Added a "Other Free Breeder Tools" cross-link grid to the two highest-traffic tool pages (<code>/dog-heat-cycle-calculator</code> and <code>/tools/heat-cycle-calculator</code>) so the calculator's accumulating authority flows to its siblings. Each sibling tool now gets a fresh inbound link from a page Google already crawls regularly.
      </p>
